    },
    {
      "id": "n-78_mMr5zmFr-V3XcI0z",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1948.2394803328266,
      "y": 1308.2363601753557,
      "width": 893.4594116210938,
      "height": 350,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b07",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 492216505,
      "version": 421,
      "versionNonce": 1850418201,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1777140198727,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Which Database we will choose ?\n\nCassendra DB -> Write-heavy database [ There would be lot of updates, so write >> read]\n\nDocument\n- id \n- docId\n- title\n- url (blob)\n- createdBy\n- createdTime\n- lastModifiedTime\n- lastModifiedBy\n... metadata",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Which Database we will choose ?\n\nCassendra DB -> Write-heavy database [ There would be lot of updates, so write >> read]\n\nDocument\n- id \n- docId\n- title\n- url (blob)\n- createdBy\n- createdTime\n- lastModifiedTime\n- lastModifiedBy\n... metadata",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "PyKTmD3zUQUgGWwxVoLa_",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2088.4753060354233,
      "y": 1925.5548377691598,
      "width": 2546.91796875,
      "height": 1025,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b08",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 488840215,
      "version": 3558,
      "versionNonce": 1468747129,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1777140211960,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Why need websocket here ? Why not Standard REST APIs ?\n\nusecase: multiple users must be able to edit the changes in a doc and they should see changes in real-time.\n\nsol:\n    1. Brute- force Approach -> using standard REST and SSE connection.\n        - userA lets say make some change \"abc\" in document -> then we submit th entire document to Edit service -> updates in DB.\n        - whenever we have change/modification in doc -> A push notification will go from server to all clients using SSE [Server side-event ]\n            -- About SSE Vs Websockets connection:\n                - both are ways to acheive real-time communication between clients & server.\n                - Websockets provides full-duplex [bi-directional] channel, SSE is a uni-direction channel, SErver -> client.\n                - SSE pushes updates to clinet whenever the doc updates in backend.\n        Problem:\n            Since we submit the entire doc everytime -> even small change means, we need to submit the whole file -> tones of heavy API calls.\n     \n    2. Locking protocol:\n        - Whenever a user is writing in doc -> we need to lock this doc for other users.\n        - Once user A is done -> Other user can see the changes and access the doc.\n        \n        Problem:\n            This is method is not concurrnet edit functionality. one user can edit doc at a time, other needs to wait !\n        \n        NOTE:\n            Two tpes of locking protocol exists.\n                1. Optimisitic Locking  -> eg: git merge  -> 2 changes creating conflict -> resolve it manually and decide which change to persist and what to remove.\n                2. Pessimistic Locking -> eg: Banking -> we follow acid [Atomicity [all or nothing rule] - consistency [valid state changes] - Isolation [multiple transaction doesnot interfere] - Durability [transaction chnages are permanent] ] property of database\n    \n    3.  WEbsocket Connector + Events Passing: \n        Solve the problems of approach 1:\n            Problem 1: we were sending the whole doc again and again to save after each key-strok changes. --> This is expensive.\n            Sol:\n                Instead of saving the whole doc again, Just save the diff !     eg: userA wants to insert(\"A\", @pos 29)\n            \n            Problem 2:  The total no of requests between client and server is very high -> anytime there is small insert in doc -> then we send that info to backend, backend push that notification to all users connected to that doc.\n            Sol:\n                We can use websocket connected here -> this reduce total no of req between client & server.\n                websocker is a bi-directional persisted connection -> opens a channel between connected users and doc.\n        \n        Problem:\n            If User A and User B trys to update in the same time and same word -> then there is conflict case.\n            - ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Why need websocket here ? Why not Standard REST APIs ?\n\nusecase: multiple users must be able to edit the changes in a doc and they should see changes in real-time.\n\nsol:\n    1. Brute- force Approach -> using standard REST and SSE connection.\n        - userA lets say make some change \"abc\" in document -> then we submit th entire document to Edit service -> updates in DB.\n        - whenever we have change/modification in doc -> A push notification will go from server to all clients using SSE [Server side-event ]\n            -- About SSE Vs Websockets connection:\n                - both are ways to acheive real-time communication between clients & server.\n                - Websockets provides full-duplex [bi-directional] channel, SSE is a uni-direction channel, SErver -> client.\n                - SSE pushes updates to clinet whenever the doc updates in backend.\n        Problem:\n            Since we submit the entire doc everytime -> even small change means, we need to submit the whole file -> tones of heavy API calls.\n     \n    2. Locking protocol:\n        - Whenever a user is writing in doc -> we need to lock this doc for other users.\n        - Once user A is done -> Other user can see the changes and access the doc.\n        \n        Problem:\n            This is method is not concurrnet edit functionality. one user can edit doc at a time, other needs to wait !\n        \n        NOTE:\n            Two tpes of locking protocol exists.\n                1. Optimisitic Locking  -> eg: git merge  -> 2 changes creating conflict -> resolve it manually and decide which change to persist and what to remove.\n                2. Pessimistic Locking -> eg: Banking -> we follow acid [Atomicity [all or nothing rule] - consistency [valid state changes] - Isolation [multiple transaction doesnot interfere] - Durability [transaction chnages are permanent] ] property of database\n    \n    3.  WEbsocket Connector + Events Passing: \n        Solve the problems of approach 1:\n            Problem 1: we were sending the whole doc again and again to save after each key-strok changes. --> This is expensive.\n            Sol:\n                Instead of saving the whole doc again, Just save the diff !     eg: userA wants to insert(\"A\", @pos 29)\n            \n            Problem 2:  The total no of requests between client and server is very high -> anytime there is small insert in doc -> then we send that info to backend, backend push that notification to all users connected to that doc.\n            Sol:\n                We can use websocket connected here -> this reduce total no of req between client & server.\n                websocker is a bi-directional persisted connection -> opens a channel between connected users and doc.\n        \n        Problem:\n            If User A and User B trys to update in the same time and same word -> then there is conflict case.\n            - ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
